# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: methionine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:methionine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The stereoisomer (*S*)-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (also referred to as L-P5C) is an intermediate metabolite in the biosynthesis and degradation of proline and arginine.
[src:methionine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In prokaryotic proline biosynthesis, GSA is synthesized from γ-glutamyl phosphate by the enzyme γ-glutamyl phosphate reductase.
[src:methionine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In most eukaryotes, GSA is synthesised from the amino acid glutamate by the bifunctional enzyme 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthase (P5CS).
[src:methionine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The human P5CS is encoded by the *ALDH18A1* gene.
[src:methionine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The enzyme pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase converts L-P5C into proline.
[src:methionine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In proline degradation, the enzyme proline dehydrogenase produces P5C from proline, and the enzyme 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate dehydrogenase converts GSA to glutamate.
[src:methionine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In many prokaryotes, proline dehydrogenase and P5C dehydrogenase form a bifunctional enzyme that prevents the release of P5C during proline degradation.
[src:methionine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] A reciprocal regulation of delta 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthetase (P5CS) and proline dehydrogenase genes controls proline levels during and after osmotic stress in plants proportional to the level of proline.
[src:methionine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] This allows an optimum level of proline to be produced from reduced nitrogen to control osmotic stress.
[src:methionine/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] The enzyme 3-hydroxyanthranilate 3,4-dioxygenase uses oxygen to cleave the aromatic ring of 3-hydroxyanthranilic acid, giving 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde.
[src:methionine/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] The kynurenine pathway of tryptophan catabolism leads to nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide and supplies the nicotinic acid component of that cofactor.
[src:methionine/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] Alternatively, 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde can be acted on by the enzyme aminocarboxymuconate-semialdehyde decarboxylase to give 2-aminomuconic semialdehyde, an unstable open-chain precursor of picolinic acid.
[src:methionine/2-aminomuconic-acid] 2-Aminomuconic acid is a six-carbon molecule bearing two carboxyl groups, two conjugated double bonds, and a primary amino substituent at carbon 2.
[src:methionine/2-aminomuconic-acid] The molecule is commonly encountered in its ionized form, 2-aminomuconate, under physiological and environmental aqueous conditions.
[src:methionine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Specific physical constants such as pKa values, solubility, and spectroscopic data are not comprehensively tabulated in the primary literature and should be added only with a verified source.
[src:methionine/2-aminomuconic-acid] In microbial biodegradation of aromatic xenobiotics, for example certain nitroaromatic compounds, where ring-cleavage pathways produce aminomuconic intermediates prior to further downstream processing.
[src:methionine/2-aminomuconic-acid] The compound appears as a catabolic intermediate in several bacterial strains studied under laboratory conditions.
[src:methionine/2-aminomuconic-acid] In the oxidative degradation of tryptophan via the kynurenine pathway, intermediates with structural relation to aminomuconate are formed during enzymatic ring opening and aldehyde oxidation steps.
[src:methionine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Wherever it appears, the ionized form 2-aminomuconate is typically the biologically relevant species.
[src:methionine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Details such as kinetic constants, mechanism and gene names vary by organism and strain and should be cited from the primary enzymology literature for each specific claim.
[src:methionine/2-aminomuconic-acid] In environmental microbiology, pathways involving 2-aminomuconate are part of bacterial systems that allow mineralization of aromatic pollutants, converting recalcitrant compounds into metabolites that join central carbon metabolism.
[src:methionine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Such pathways are of interest for biodegradation and bioremediation research.
[src:methionine/2-aminomuconic-semialdehyde] 2-Aminomuconic semialdehyde is an intermediate in the kynurenine pathway of tryptophan metabolism, which leads to picolinic acid or quinolinic acid.
[src:methionine/2-aminomuconic-semialdehyde] The enzyme aminocarboxymuconate-semialdehyde decarboxylase produces it from 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde, a compound which would form quinolinic acid in the absence of that enzyme.
[src:methionine/2-aminomuconic-semialdehyde] 2-Aminomuconic semialdehyde itself is chemically unstable and spontaneously ring-closes to picolinic acid, with loss of water.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the glycolytic pathway, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is dephosphorylated to form 3-phosphoglyceric acid in a coupled reaction producing two ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] The single phosphate group left on the 3-PGA molecule then moves from an end carbon to a central carbon, producing 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This phosphate group relocation is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate mutase, an enzyme that also catalyzes the reverse reaction.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 5.4.2.1 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00631 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the light-independent reactions (also known as the Calvin-Benson cycle), two 3-phosphoglycerate molecules are synthesized.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] RuBP, a 5-carbon sugar, undergoes carbon fixation, catalyzed by the rubisco enzyme, to become an unstable 6-carbon intermediate.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This intermediate is then cleaved into two, separate 3-carbon molecules of 3-PGA.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] G3P eventually reacts to form the sugars such as glucose or fructose or more complex starches.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Glycerate 3-phosphate (formed from 3-phosphoglycerate) is also a precursor for serine, which, in turn, can create cysteine and glycine through the homocysteine cycle.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] 3-phosphoglycerate can be separated and measured using paper chromatography as well as with column chromatography and other chromatographic separation methods.
[src:methionine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] It can be identified using both gas-chromatography and liquid-chromatography mass spectrometry and has been optimized for evaluation using tandem MS techniques.
[src:methionine/4-dimethylaminophenol] Heating dimethylaniline N-oxide in concentrated sulfuric acid causes a Bamberger rearrangement to 2- and 4-dimethylaminophenols.
[src:methionine/4-dimethylaminophenol] 4-Dimethylaminophenol has been used as an antidote for cyanide poisoning.
[src:methionine/4-dimethylaminophenol] It has also been shown to be effective in treating hydrogen sulfide toxicity.
[src:methionine/4-dimethylaminophenol] This is suitable as an emergency treatment only; treatment must be followed up with sodium thiosulfate or cobalamin.
[src:methionine/4-dimethylaminophenol] In an animal model, it has shown effectiveness when given intramuscularly.
[src:methionine/4-dimethylaminophenol] Though, intramuscular injection should be avoid due to the probability of muscular necrosis after injection.
[src:methionine/4-dimethylaminophenol] Intravenous injection is recommended in a dose of 250 mg.
[src:methionine/4-hydroxyphenylpyruvic-acid] It is an intermediary compound in the biosynthesis of scytonemin.
[src:methionine/methionine] Methionine was first isolated in 1921 by John Howard Mueller.
[src:methionine/methionine] It was named by Satoru Odake in 1925, as an abbreviation of its structural description 2-amino-4-(**meth**ylt**hio**)butanoic acid.
[src:methionine/methionine] Methionine (abbreviated as **Met** or **M**; encoded by the codon AUG) is an α-amino acid that is used in the biosynthesis of proteins.
[src:methionine/methionine] In nuclear genes of eukaryotes and in Archaea, methionine is coded for by the start codon, meaning it indicates the start of the coding region and is the first amino acid produced in a nascent polypeptide during mRNA translation.
[src:methionine/methionine] Cysteine and methionine are the two sulfur-containing proteinogenic amino acids.
[src:methionine/methionine] Excluding the few exceptions where methionine may act as a redox sensor (e.g., methionine sulfoxide), methionine residues do not have a catalytic role.
[src:methionine/methionine] This is in contrast to cysteine residues, where the thiol group has a catalytic role in many proteins.
[src:methionine/methionine] The thioether within methionine does however have a minor structural role due to the stability effect of S/π interactions between the side chain sulfur atom and aromatic amino acids in one-third of all known protein structures.
[src:methionine/methionine] This lack of a strong role is reflected in experiments where little effect is seen in proteins where methionine is replaced by norleucine, a straight hydrocarbon sidechain amino acid which lacks the thioether.
[src:methionine/methionine] It has been conjectured that norleucine was present in early versions of the genetic code, but methionine intruded into the final version of the genetic code due to its role in the cofactor *S*-adenosylmethionine (rSAM).
[src:methionine/methionine] This situation is not unique and may have occurred with ornithine and arginine.
[src:methionine/methionine] Methionine is one of only two amino acids encoded by a single codon (AUG) in the standard genetic code (tryptophan, encoded by UGG, is the other).
[src:methionine/methionine] In reflection to the evolutionary origin of its codon, the other AUN codons encode isoleucine, which is also a hydrophobic amino acid.
[src:methionine/methionine] In the mitochondrial genome of several organisms, including metazoa and yeast, the codon AUA also encodes for methionine.
[src:methionine/methionine] In the standard genetic code AUA codes for isoleucine and the respective tRNA (*ileX* in *Escherichia coli*) uses the unusual base lysidine (bacteria) or agmatidine (archaea) to discriminate against AUG.
[src:methionine/methionine] The methionine codon AUG is also the most common start codon.
[src:methionine/methionine] A "Start" codon is message for a ribosome that signals the initiation of protein translation from mRNA when the AUG codon is in a Kozak consensus sequence.
[src:methionine/methionine] As a consequence, methionine is often incorporated into the *N*-terminal position of proteins in eukaryotes and archaea during translation, although it can be removed by post-translational modification.
[src:methionine/methionine] In bacteria, the derivative *N*-formylmethionine is used as the initial amino acid.
[src:methionine/methionine] The methionine-derivative *S*-adenosylmethionine (rSAM) is a cofactor that serves mainly as a methyl donor. rSAM is composed of an adenosyl molecule (via 5′ carbon) attached to the sulfur of methionine.
[src:methionine/methionine] It is a sulfonium cation that releases a methyl radical upon reduction.
[src:methionine/methionine] As an essential amino acid, methionine is not synthesized *de novo* in humans and other animals, which must ingest methionine or methionine-containing proteins.
[src:methionine/methionine] In plants and microorganisms, methionine biosynthesis belongs to the aspartate family, along with threonine and lysine (via diaminopimelate, but not via α-aminoadipate).
[src:methionine/methionine] The main backbone is derived from aspartic acid, while the sulfur may come from cysteine, methanethiol, or hydrogen sulfide.
[src:methionine/methionine] The pathway using cysteine is called the "transsulfuration pathway", while the pathway using hydrogen sulfide (or methanethiol) is called "direct-sulfurylation pathway".
[src:methionine/methionine] CysK and CysM are homologues, but belong to the PLP fold type III clade.
[src:methionine/methionine] Methionine is converted to *S*-adenosylmethionine (rSAM) by (1) methionine adenosyltransferase.
[src:methionine/methionine] rSAM serves as a methyl donor in many (2) methyltransferase reactions, and is converted to *S*-adenosylhomocysteine (SAH).
[src:methionine/methionine] Methionine can be regenerated from homocysteine via (4) methionine synthase in a reaction that requires vitamin B12 as a cofactor.
[src:methionine/methionine] Homocysteine can also be remethylated using glycine betaine (*N*,*N*,*N*-trimethylglycine, TMG) to methionine via the enzyme betaine-homocysteine methyltransferase (E.C.2.1.1.5, BHMT).
[src:methionine/methionine] BHMT makes up to 1.5% of all the soluble protein of the liver, and recent evidence suggests that it may have a greater influence on methionine and homocysteine homeostasis than methionine synthase.
[src:methionine/methionine] Homocysteine can be converted to cysteine.
[src:methionine/methionine] The industrial synthesis combines acrolein, methanethiol, and cyanide, which affords the hydantoin.
[src:methionine/methionine] Racemic methionine can also be synthesized from diethyl sodium phthalimidomalonate by alkylation with chloroethylmethylsulfide (ClCH2CH2SCH3) followed by hydrolysis and decarboxylation.
[src:methionine/methionine] There is inconclusive clinical evidence on methionine supplementation.
[src:methionine/methionine] Dietary restriction of methionine can lead to bone-related disorders.
[src:methionine/methionine] Overconsumption of methionine, the methyl group donor in DNA methylation, is related to cancer growth in a number of studies.
[src:methionine/methionine] The Food and Nutrition Board of the U.S.
[src:methionine/methionine] Institute of Medicine set Recommended Dietary Allowances (RDAs) for essential amino acids in 2002.
[src:methionine/methionine] For methionine combined with cysteine, for adults 19 years and older, 19 mg/kg body weight/day.
[src:methionine/methionine] This translates to about 1.33 grams per day for a 70 kilogram individual.
[src:methionine/methionine] High levels of methionine can be found in eggs, meat, and fish; sesame seeds, Brazil nuts, and some other plant seeds; and cereal grains.
[src:methionine/methionine] Most fruits and vegetables contain very little.
[src:methionine/methionine] Most legumes, though protein dense, are low in methionine.
[src:methionine/methionine] Proteins without adequate methionine are not considered to be complete proteins.
[src:methionine/methionine] For that reason, racemic methionine is sometimes added as an ingredient to pet foods.
[src:methionine/methionine] Loss of methionine has been linked to senile greying of hair.
[src:methionine/methionine] Its lack leads to a buildup of hydrogen peroxide in hair follicles, a reduction in tyrosinase effectiveness, and a gradual loss of hair color.
[src:methionine/methionine] Methionine raises the intracellular concentration of glutathione, thereby promoting antioxidant-mediated cell defense and redox regulation.
[src:methionine/methionine] It also protects cells against dopamine induced nigral cell loss by binding oxidative metabolites.
[src:methionine/methionine] Methionine is an intermediate in the biosynthesis of cysteine, carnitine, taurine, lecithin, phosphatidylcholine, and other phospholipids.
[src:methionine/methionine] Improper conversion of methionine can lead to atherosclerosis due to accumulation of homocysteine.
[src:methionine/methionine] DL-Methionine is sometimes given as a supplement to dogs; It helps reduce the chances of kidney stones in dogs.
[src:methionine/methionine] Methionine is also known to increase the urinary excretion of quinidine by acidifying the urine.
[src:methionine/methionine] Aminoglycoside antibiotics used to treat urinary tract infections work best in alkaline conditions, and urinary acidification from using methionine can reduce its effectiveness.
[src:methionine/methionine] If a dog is on a diet that acidifies the urine, methionine should not be used.
[src:methionine/methionine] Methionine is allowed as a supplement to organic poultry feed under the US certified organic program.
[src:methionine/methionine] Methionine can be used as a nontoxic pesticide option against giant swallowtail caterpillars, which are a serious pest to orange crops.
[src:methionine/methionine] More and more studies show that restricting methionine intake can increase the lifespan of some animals.
[src:methionine/methionine] In 2005, a study showed that restricting methionine intake without energy restriction in rodents increases their lifespan.
